<h2>Update 470G # Date 21 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 14 - SICKNESS ALLOWANCE - Claims from current and former students. See guidelines 14.5020 to 14.5031.</p>
<p>Recipients of an Australian Postgraduate Award with a Stipend may be considered to have suffered a loss of income if they have to suspend their studies/research because of a temporary illness.</p>
<h2>Update 469G # Date 21 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 24 - BEREAVEMENT PAYMENTS - Bereavement payments. See guidelines 24.000 to 24.7201.</p>
<p>This amendment replaces the entire chapter 24, which has been updated to reflect the new payments of partner and parenting allowance which were introduced from 1 July 1995.</p>
<h2>Update 468G # Date 21 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 43 - PARTNER ALLOWANCE - Bereavement payments for partner allowees. See guidelines 43.4800 to 43.4803.</p>
<p>These changes relate to qualification for bereavement payments to partner allowees.</p>
<h2>Update 467G # Date 21 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 1 - GENERAL PROCEDURES inc. TAX FILE NUMBER EXEMPTIONS - Assurance of Support - Recoverability and clarification. See guidelines 1) 1.9000 to 1.9011 2) 1.9100 to 1.9202 3) 1.9300 to 1.10005.</p>
<p>1) The effect of Assurances of Support on recoverability of PA, PgA, WA and YTA. Clarification of procedures for release of bonds paid by assurers.</p>
<p>2) Clarification of the date of effect of assurances of support. Additions regarding coding for PA. PA, WA and YTA where an assurance of support exists. Clarification of assurance of support period.</p>
<p>3) Clarification of new claim procedures in cases where an assurance of support exists. Changes resulting from PA, WA, PA and YTA being recoverable. Update of location of records and contacts resulting from devolution of State functions. Clarification of procedures for domestic violence cases. Changes to categories of persons exempt from newly arrived residents waiting period.</p>
<h2 id="7september1995">Update 466G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Special Assistance for the Older Unemployed. See guidelines 12.1400 to 12.1408.</p>
<p>There are a number of measures designed to assist the older unemployed including reduced reporting, changes to activity testing, allowed participation in voluntary work, entitlement to higher rates of payment, and access to other entitlements such as pharmaceutical allowance, telephone allowance and a Pensioner Concession Card. Other forms of income support include mature age allowance and widow allowance.</p>
<h2>Update 465G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Activity Test Exemption for Refugees. See guideline 12.3310.</p>
<p>Refugees are now able to be exempted from the activity test for a maximum of 13 weeks during the first 13 weeks after they arrive in Australia.</p>
<h2>Update 464G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 4 - NEGLIGENCE CLAIMS, ACT OF GRACE PAYMENTS - Deed of release. See guideline 4.11200.</p>
<p>Amendment to the Deed of Release to be used in settlement of finance direction 21/3 (negligence) and act of grace claims.</p>
<h2>Update 463G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Payment pending review of a decision to impose a deferment period. See guidelines 12.10502 to 12.10505.</p>
<p>Payment may now be continued pending the outcome of a review of a decision to impose a deferment period. Guidelines have been set for the exercise of this discretion.</p>
<h2>Update 462G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 14 - SICKNESS ALLOWANCE - Timing of reviews. See guideline 14.11000.</p>
<p>This change corrects the type of sickness allowance review that is conducted at 64 weeks from a mail review to a field review.</p>
<h2>Update 461G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Application of financial hardship provisions- Rural Adjustment Scheme Certification.</p>
<p>These provisions lapsed on 30 November 1993 and are therefore no longer applicable and should be deleted from the Guide. Previously guideline 27.16500 to 27.16506.</p>
<h2>Update 460G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 14 - SICKNESS ALLOWANCE - Assessment of medical evidence. See guidelines 14.8200.</p>
<p>This change updates the address for mail orders of the 'Sickness Allowance Medical Certificate' (Form SU415).</p>
<h2>Update 459G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Self employment. See guidelines 12.250 to 12.265.</p>
<p>The Employment Secretary (or delegate in the Commonwealth Employment Service(CES)) may approve participation in activities that will lead to sustainable employment and financial independence or at least skills and experience that will assist the person in finding full-time employment.</p>
<h2>Update 458G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Vocational training courses and labour market programs - approved activities. See guidelines 12.2600 to 12.2624.</p>
<p>Approved activities include certain English language courses for the period of the activity agreement. Customers undertaking courses longer than 4 weeks advised of alternate 'Application for Payment' (Form SU19) lodgement options.</p>
<h2>Update 457G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Employment - earnings verification. See guidelines 27.8630 to 27.8635.</p>
<p>Earnings of a claimant or partner do not need verification where the declared amount is sufficient to preclude payment of benefit. The declared earnings may also be accepted without verification if they are consistent with the type of work performed in relation to the time worked and there is no reason to doubt their authenticity.</p>
<h2>Update 456G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Customers can continue to be regarded as unemployed where casual earnings preclude payment for up to five fortnights. See guidelines 12.121 to 12.126.</p>
<p>After five fortnights a customer can have their payment continued if their income is reduced. Payment cannot be reinstated where earnings preclude payment for six or more fortnights.</p>
<p>Customers may engage in the development of, or participation in, a group or co-operative enterprise as part of an Activity Agreement. See guidelines 12.141 to 12.145.</p>
<p>Customers may engage in the development of, or participation in, a group or co-operative enterprise as part of an Activity Agreement with the Commonwealth Employment Service or a Case Management Agreement with an independent Contracted Case Manager.</p>
<h2>Update 455G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Voluntary work - full time. See guidelines 12.402 to 12.403.</p>
<p>For customers over 18 and up to 64 who have a current Activity Agreement with the Commonwealth Employment Service, no restriction is placed on the duration of the full time voluntary work as long as the activity is approved.</p>
<h2>Update 454G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 26 - EMPLOYMENT AND EDUCATION PAYMENTS - 1) Eligibility choices where customer has casual work expected to last less than 12 weeks. 2)Employment Entry Payment is not income tested. Guideline covers Youth Training Allowance (YTA) as well.</p>
<p>1) Where casual work is expected to last less than 12 weeks customers can choose to keep lodging forms SU19 or to have their payment cancelled and apply for Employment Entry Payment (EEP) - see guidelines 26.1100 to 26.1107.</p>
<p>2) Minor amendment to guidelines- see guidelines 26.1200 to 26.1201.</p>
<h2>Update 453G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Continuation forms - exemption/temporary exemption from personal lodgement. See guidelines 12.15300 to 12.15401 and 12.15800 to 12.15805.</p>
<p>Customers may be exempted/temporarily exempted from personal lodgement of their continuation form where they are engaged in an approved activity or are working on their due-to-lodge date.</p>
<h2>Update 452G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Abbreviated claim procedures where reclaiming within 26 weeks of cancellation. See guidelines 12.13900 to 12.13911 and 12.13931.</p>
<p>Customers reclaiming allowance within 26 weeks of cancellation of their last payment are eligible for abbreviated claim procedures.</p>
<h2>Update 451G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Verification of approved activities. See guideline 12.17900.</p>
<p>Text change only - client to customer.</p>
<h2>Update 450G # Date 7 September 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Casual employment. See guideline 12.17200.</p>
<p>Customers can continue to be regarded as unemployed where casual earnings preclude payment for up to five fortnights.</p>
<h2 id="24august1995">Update 449G # Date 24 August 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Income test treatment of 'Packaged' investments. See guidelines 27.14450 to 27.14455.</p>
<p>In 1994/95, several Friendly Societies passed resolutions to amend the Friendly Society Rules that govern certain policies. Under the Friendly Society Act, varying a Rule does not necessarily create a new contract but merely varies the existing contract. Accordingly, switching from any saved investment into other sub-funds within the one Friendly Society contract does not constitute a realisation under section 9(10) of the Act.</p>
<h2>Update 448G # Date 24 August 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - Reviews on portable payments - avoiding cancellation of pension etc. See guidelines 42.820 to 42.823.</p>
<p>If wife pensioners overseas experience a temporary increase in income, wife pension is to be suspended rather than cancelled.</p>
<h2>Update 447G # Date 24 August 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Commencement of full time study - payment to customer may continue. See guideline 12.5310.</p>
<p>Customers participating in Commonwealth Employment Service approved courses of up to 12 months duration, which would normally attract payment under a prescribed education scheme such as AUSTUDY, may continue to receive payment subject to normal requirements.</p>
<h2>Update 446G # Date 24 August 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Superannuation and rollover investments. See guideline 27.13182.</p>
<p>This amendment gives a further explanation on the treatment of superannuation salary sacrifices for customers over retirement age.</p>
<h2>Update 445G # Date 24 August 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Change in deeming rate. See guideline 27.11310.</p>
<p>The Minister announced, with effect from 1 July 1995, a change in the deeming rate from 4% to 5%.</p>
<h2>Update 444G # Date 24 August 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Vocational training courses and labour market programs. See guidelines 12.2600 to 12.2782.</p>
<p>These changes reflect the current situation with the treatment of labour market programs, including entitlement to EEPs and reclaiming.</p>
<h2>Update 443G # Date 24 August 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - Portability - portability restriction for certain pensions and allowances - wife and widow B pension. See guideline 42.247.</p>
<p>Autonomous wife pensioners overseas may transfer to agreement entitlement after 1 July 1995 without having to lodge a claim.</p>
<h2>Update 442G # Date 24 August 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Failure to attend or contact for an interview. See guidelines 12.9100 to 12.9101.</p>
