<h2>Update 339G # Date 9 March 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 1 - GENERAL PROCEDURES inc. TAX FILE NUMBER EXEMPTIONS - Rent Assistance. See guidelines 1.5400 to 1.5451.</p>
<p>These changes emphasise the importance of document integrity for Rent Assistance purposes and the need to pay particular attention to shared accommodation arrangements.</p>
<h2 id="23february1995">Update 338G # Date 23 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 20 - MOBILITY ALLOWANCE - Need for a medical report. See guidelines 20.400 to 20.403.</p>
<p>Description of the Mobility Allowance report (MA2).</p>
<h2>Update 337G # Date 23 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - Wife pensions. See guidelines 42.240 to 42.247.</p>
<p>Minor editing of heading in guideline 42.240 and information about the phasing out of wife pension in guideline 42.247.</p>
<h2>Update 336G # Date 23 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - (1) Notification of recipient going overseas. See guideline 42.140. (2) Bereavement Allowance. See guideline 42.120. (3) Portability Arrangements New Zealand and United Kingdom. See guidelines 42.130 to 42.132.</p>
<p>(1) Recipient notification notices now state that pensioners must notify DSS within 14 days of deciding to go overseas. Information products, such as the Handbook and Age Pension News, point out that 6 to 8 weeks notice would be helpful to DSS.</p>
<p>(2) Bereavement allowance is not covered under the Agreement with New Zealand and its portability is not affected by the portability restrictions of the Agreement.</p>
<p>(3) The amendment stresses that the Agreements with New Zealand and the United Kingdom do not have general portability provisions like Australia's other Agreements.</p>
<h2>Update 335G # Date 23 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Moving superannuation monies between superannuation investments. See guidelines 27.13190 to 27.13192.</p>
<p>Clarification of the treatment of amounts moved from one superannuation investment to another.</p>
<h2>Update 334G # Date 23 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - (1) Portability - pre departure arrangements. See guideline 42.420. (2) Portability - pre departure arrangements. See guidelines 42.440 to 42.444. (3) Portability - Wife pensions. See guideline 42.450. (4) Portability - sole parent and widow B. See guidelines 42.510 to 42.521.</p>
<p>(1) Departure certificates can be issued only when portability is confirmed.</p>
<p>(2) DSP portability is not to be delayed pending the results of a pre-departure medical examination.</p>
<p>(3) Wife pension portability should not be approved until a decision is made on portability of the husband's pension.</p>
<p>(4) Clarifies that de jure widows in receipt of sole parent pension or widow B pension are not subject to proportional portability after 12 months absence.</p>
<h2>Update 333G # Date 23 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - (1) Portability - method of payment. See guidelines 42.740 to 42.742. (2) Portability - pre-departure arrangements. See guidelines 42.450 to 42.751. (3) Portability - payment arrangements. See guideline 42.780.</p>
<p>(1) Portability payments to pensioners in Ireland are made in pounds sterling and the IOB decides if a long term portable pension may be paid in Australia.</p>
<p>(2) Portability should not be delayed pending the results of a pre-departure medical examination.</p>
<p>(3) Records should not be transferred to the IOB until long term portability is determined.</p>
<h2>Update 332G # Date 23 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - (1) Monitoring the CFP legislation. See guidelines 42.2400 to 42.2401. (2) Applying the CFP legislation. See guidelines 42.2500 to 42.2501.</p>
<p>(1) Monitoring the CFP legislation for widow allowance.</p>
<p>(2) Reference inserted to the completion of Module O in relation to Form SU16 (widow allowance).</p>
<h2>Update 331G # Date 23 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - (1) CFP and widow allowance. See guidelines 42.2000 to 42.2001. (2) CFP, widow allowance and blind pensioners. See guidelines 42.2010 to 42.2014.</p>
<p>(1) Extension of the comparable foreign payment provisions to widow allowance.</p>
<p>(2) Extension of the comparable foreign payment provisions to widow allowance and procedures for obtaining CFP assessment information from blind claimants.</p>
<h2>Update 330G # Date 23 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 1 - GENERAL PROCEDURES inc. TAX FILE NUMBER EXEMPTIONS - Completion of Module O by widow allowance claimants. See guideline 1.2910.</p>
<p>Widow allowance claimants are affected by the comparable foreign payment provisions. Module O must therefore be completed if a claimant discloses on the claim form (SU16) that she has lived outside Australia.</p>
<h2>Update 329G # Date 23 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 1 - GENERAL PROCEDURES inc. TAX FILE NUMBER EXEMPTIONS - Pension claims under Agreements with New Zealand and United Kingdom. See guidelines 1.8900 to 1.8904.</p>
<p>The amendment stresses that Regional Offices continue to process claims for Australian pensions lodged under the Agreements with New Zealand and the United Kingdom.</p>
<h2 id="9february1995">Update 328G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 45 - YOUTH TRAINING ALLOWANCE - new chapter . See guidelines 45.000 to 45.20001.</p>
<p>Introduction of new payment for unemployed under 18 year olds - replacing JSA under 18. Legislation is contained in the Student and Youth Assistance Act 1973.</p>
<h2>Update 327G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 46 - WIDOW ALLOWANCE - new chapter. See guidelines 46.000 to 46.3304.</p>
<p>Widow allowance is a new payment available to older women who lose the support of their partner later in life and who have no recent workforce experience. Widow allowance became payable from 1 January 1995.</p>
<h2>Update 326G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 39 - MATURE AGE ALLOWANCE - Residency requirements for payment of mature age partner allowance.. See guidelines 39.2400 to 39.2401.</p>
<p>To be eligible for mature age partner allowance, a claimant must be an 'Australian resident', as defined in section 7(1) of the Act.</p>
<h2>Update 325G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 2 - METHODS OF PAYMENT AND TAXATION - Taxability of mature age allowance and mature age partner allowance. See guidelines 2.8000 to 2.8003.</p>
<p>Mature age allowance is taxable. Mature age partner allowance is not taxable for the 1993-94 and 1994-95 financial years. Mature Age Partner Allowance will become taxable from 1 July 1995.</p>
<h2>Update 324G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 25 - NON-CASH BENEFITS - Eligibility criteria for CAAS. See guidelines 25.20300 to 25.20305.</p>
<p>New section concerning client eligibility for assistance to buy care items for people who have a permanent bladder or bowel condition.</p>
<h2>Update 323G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Life Interests. See guidelines 27.15200 to 27.15201.</p>
<p>Assessment of life interest under the asset test if life interest created by deceased partner's Will in respect of deaths on or after 19 May 1994.</p>
<h2>Update 322G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 6 - DISABILITY SUPPORT PENSION - Eligibility criteria for CAAS. See guidelines 6.5200 to 6.5205.</p>
<p>New section concerning client eligibility for assistance to buy care items for people who have a permanent bladder or bowel condition.</p>
<h2>Update 321G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Exempt assets - house and curtilage. See guidelines 27.15000 to 27.15014.</p>
<p>A larger than average houseblock, which may have a separate title, but is less than two hectares in area can still be considered as part of the exempt curtilage.</p>
<h2>Update 320G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Excluded income. See guidelines 27.9400 to 27.9401.</p>
<p>The Guide currently gives explanations of some types of excluded income, but by no means all. Staff should acquaint themselves with all the categories contained in subsection 8(8) of the Act.</p>
<h2>Update 319G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Hardship - unrealisable assets. See guideline 27.16165.</p>
<p>Correction of rate for calculating notional income for JSA from $0.75 to $1.00.</p>
<h2>Update 318G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - War widow's pension. See guidelines 27.7210 to 27.7227.</p>
<p>War widow's pension - effect on social security pensions since November 1986.</p>
<h2>Update 317G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 17 - FAMILY PAYMENT - Companies. See guideline 17.9400.</p>
<p>Directors and shareholders of private companies are not employers.</p>
<h2>Update 316G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Assessment of investment income. See guidelines 27.13900 to 27.13909.</p>
<p>Clarification of amounts allowable as a deduction of investment and disposal costs.</p>
<h2>Update 315G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 1 - GENERAL PROCEDURE inc. TAX FILE NUMBER EXEMPTIONS - Valuation procedures. See guideline 1.6200.</p>
<p>The procedures for seeking Australian Valuation Office valuations of real estate prior to grant of pension, benefit or allowance are clarified and expanded to cover situations where hardship is likely because of valuation delays.</p>
<h2>Update 314G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Valuation procedures. See guidelines 27.15920 to 27.15928.</p>
<p>The procedures for seeking Australian Valuation Office valuations of real estate prior to grant of pension, benefit or allowance are clarified and expanded to cover situations where hardship is likely because of valuation delays.</p>
<h2>Update 313G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Income review - employment - earnings credit. See guidelines 27.17510 to 27.17519.</p>
<p>To include carer pension in list of "eligible pensions" that recipients of which are able to have an earnings credit account. Implementation of carer pensioners eligible for earnings credits occurred 1 July 1993. Updating guideline to reflect initiative.</p>
<h2>Update 312G # Date 9 February 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 14 - SICKNESS ALLOWANCE - Claims from current and former students. See guidelines 14.5000 to 14.5021.</p>
<p>From 1 January 1995 a loss of AUSTUDY or ABSTUDY will be accepted as a loss of income for sickness allowance.</p>
<h2 id="26january1995">Update 311G # Date 26 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - The Deposit Accounts and Direct Investments System (SAV). See guidelines 27.11000 to 27.11304.</p>
<p>Details of clients' at-call deposit accounts in banks, building societies and credit unions and other direct investments are recorded on the Deposit Accounts and Direct Investments System (SAV). The SAV facility has two sub-facilities. The At-Call Deposit Account Facility that has a data base of interest rates for at-call accounts available from financial institutions in Australia. The Other Direct Investment Facility records other direct investments such as bonds and term deposits. This sub-facility is not linked to a data base of interest rates. Minor changes also made to the details about home loan offset accounts.</p>
<h2>Update 310G # Date 26 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 22 - CHILDCARE ASSISTANCE - Childcare Assistance . See guidelines 22.000 to 22.4101.</p>
<p>The key changes are in relation to notification and re-application provisions, net rental property losses and estimates of base year income.</p>
<h2>Update 309G # Date 26 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Breaches and deferment periods. See guidelines 12.9000 to 12.9001.</p>
<p>Breaches of Social Security Act have been re-categorised. Deferment periods arising from breaches have also been changed. Minor changes in terminology relating to breaches and deferment periods. Relationship between deferment periods and waiting periods has changed.</p>
<h2>Update 308G # Date 26 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Breaches and deferment periods. See guideline 12.7200.</p>
<p>Breaches of Social Security Act have been re-categorised. Deferment periods arising from breaches have also been changed. Minor changes in terminology relating to breaches and deferment periods. Relationship between deferment periods and waiting periods has changed.</p>
<h2>Update 307G # Date 26 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Breaches and deferment periods. See guidelines 12.7000 to 12.7003.</p>
<p>Breaches of Social Security Act have been re-categorised. Deferment periods arising from breaches have also been changed. Minor changes in terminology relating to breaches and deferment periods. Relationship between deferment periods and waiting periods has changed.</p>
<h2>Update 306G # Date 26 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Breaches and deferment periods. See guideline 12.10600.</p>
<p>Breaches of Social Security Act have been re-categorised. Deferment periods arising from breaches have also been changed. Minor changes in terminology relating to breaches and deferment periods. Relationship between deferment periods and waiting periods has changed.</p>
<h2>Update 305G # Date 26 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 8 - CARER PENSION - 1. These guidelines describe the procedures to be followed when a person enquires about eligibility for carer pension before taking up full-time care. See guidelines 8.900 to 8.907. 2. Participation in employment, education or training.</p>
<p>1. It is possible to give a claimant an indication of whether they may qualify for carer pension prior to them assuming the full-time caring role.</p>
<p>2. To clarify that a decision to cancel payment should be made under section 198(1) if the care requirements are not being met. Section 198(2AA) does not give authority to cancel solely because the 10 hours per week allowed for employment, education or training has been exceeded.</p>
<h2 id="12january1995">Update 304G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - YOUNG HOMELESS ALLOWANCE. Guidelines 12.21000 to 12.21703 have been deleted as this subject is now covered by chapter 44 - Homeless Rate.</p>
<h2>Update 303G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 44 - HOMELESS RATE - new chapter replacing Part Q of chapter 12. See guidelines 44.000 to 44.8103.</p>
<p>The homeless rate (also known as Young Homeless Allowance (YHA) is not a payment in its own right, it is the higher rate of job search allowance (JSA), sickness allowance (SA) or special benefit payable to a 'homeless person'. The homeless rate is equivalent to the independent rate of payment.</p>
<h2>Update 302G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Assistance with claims for overseas pensions. See guidelines 27.4100 (deleted).</p>
<p>The names and addresses of overseas social security organisations are now in guideline 42.2331.</p>
<h2>Update 301G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 1 - GENERAL PROCEDURES inc. TAX FILE NUMBER EXEMPTIONS - Verifying qualifying residence for claimants who have lived in Agreement countries. See guidelines 1.8900 to 1.8904.</p>
<p>Up to date information on International Social Security Agreements and the new claim action required when claimant relies on residence or contributions in an Agreement country to qualify residentially for an Australian payment.</p>
<h2>Update 300G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - new chapter. See guidelines 42.000 to 42.2531.</p>
<p>The OLI Portability Manual is now incorporated as Part A of chapter 42 of the Guide. In addition, Part B of chapter 42 deals with policy and procedures for the Comparable Foreign Payment Provisions, introduced from 20 March 1994 and, until now, available only in National Instructions.</p>
<h2>Update 299G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 6 - DISABILITY SUPPORT PENSION - Applications rejected because impairment is less than 20%. See guidelines 6.400 to 6.604.</p>
<p>Sets out procedures for disability support officer cases which have been rejected as the impairment level is less than 20%.</p>
<h2>Update 298G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 1 - GENERAL PROCEDURES inc TAX FILE NUMBER EXEMPTIONS - Claimant born overseas. See guidelines 1.2900 to 1.2953.</p>
<p>Interviewing claimants who have lived and worked overseas - claiming pensions from comparable foreign payment countries and non-Agreement countries. Filling out Module O and recording overseas work history and residence in New Zealand.</p>
<h2>Update 296G &amp; 297G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Family payment - income and assets test rates - proof of income/proof of estimates. See guidelines 27.25600 to 27.25623, 27.25800 to 27.25804 and 27.27120 to 27.27140.</p>
<p>From the beginning of the 1994 family payment end of year review process, clients will no longer be required to provide documentary evidence of income.</p>
<h2>Update 295G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - JSA/NSA recipients undertaking community correctional orders in excess of 20 hours per week. See guidelines 12.220 to 12.225.</p>
<p>That job search allowance/newstart allowance (JSA/NSA) recipients can have community service orders written into their activity agreements provided that the correctional order activity can be shown to be a measure designed to eliminate or reduce any disadvantage the client faces in terms of their job seeking or employability.</p>
<h2>Update 294G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Transitional arrangements for temporarily incapacitated clients transferring from JSA to NSA. See guideline 12.13800 to 12.13802.</p>
<p>A job search allowance (JSA) recipient whose incapacity end date exceeds the recipient's JSA end date may be posted a newstart allowance (NSA) claim form by the CES. The recipient will be eligible for NSA provided the NSA claim is lodged and the recipient is willing to enter into a Newstart Activity Agreement once the incapacity end date has expired.</p>
<h2>Update 293G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Variation to normal lodgement - interstate lodgement. See guidelines 12.16100 to 12.16103.</p>
<p>SU19s lodged interstate and therefore out of the home office were previously faxed to the home office for processing. Form can now be processed at the interstate office but, after processing, should still be returned to the home office for storage.</p>
<h2>Update 292G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 27 - DETERMINING RATES OF PAYMENT - Family Payment - Income and Assets Tests Rates. See guidelines 27.25200 to 27.25288.</p>
<p>Inclusion of Employer Provided Benefits and Net Rental Property Losses in Family Payment Income test.</p>
<h2>Update 291G # Date 12 January 1995</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 17 - FAMILY PAYMENT - Family Payment Income Test - inclusion of net rental property losses. See guidelines 17.8000 to 17.8302.</p>
<p>Details change to Family Payment Income Test by inclusion of net rental property losses.</p>
